                    <comment id="12382156" author="olegk" created="Sun, 13 Feb 2005 22:04:56 +0000"  >HTTP/1.1 for CONNECT method is not really hardcoded. The trouble is that the&lt;br/&gt;
CONNECT method takes its parameters from the client, ignoring those set at the&lt;br/&gt;
method and host level. Anyways, it is a serious bug. I&amp;#39;ll start working on a fix&lt;br/&gt;
&lt;br/&gt;
Oleg</comment>
                    <comment id="12382157" author="olegk" created="Mon, 14 Feb 2005 02:08:40 +0000"  >Riad,&lt;br/&gt;
&lt;br/&gt;
My apologies. You are absolutely right. HTTP/1.1 for CONNECT was indeed&lt;br/&gt;
hardcoded. The rationale behind this decision probably was HTTP spec compliance.&lt;br/&gt;
HTTP CONNECT method was initially defined in HTTP/1.1 specification only.&lt;br/&gt;
However, there are enough HTTP/1.0 proxies which implement certain HTTP/1.1&lt;br/&gt;
features, including SSL tunneling support. So, the decision to restrict HTTP&lt;br/&gt;
CONNECT to HTTP/1.1 was certainly wrong. My bad. &lt;br/&gt;
&lt;br/&gt;
A patch coming shortly&lt;br/&gt;
&lt;br/&gt;
Oleg</comment>
                    <comment id="12382158" author="olegk" created="Mon, 14 Feb 2005 02:10:03 +0000"  >Created an attachment (id=14271)&lt;br/&gt;
